IPAD-294.name: Discard changes to closed cases on server.

* Create a case with a form or two, and populate the forms a little bit.
* Have the case loaded into two iPads in the same state (showing same form values).
* Take iPad A offline (airplane mode).
* From iPad B, close the case. Wait a couple of minutes for those changes to reach the server.
* Log into the web, and observe the case in the review section.
** "Print Form" and see the PDF to observe the form state.
** Close the print form tab.
* From iPad A, add some form changes.
* Bring iPad A back online (turn off airplane mode).
* Wait a couple of minutes for the changes to reach the server.
* The case should disappear from iPad A.
* Review the case from the web again:
** "Print Form" and see the PDF to observe the form state.
** The changes made on iPad A should not appear.

IPAD-194.name: An All Alerts option should be available in iPad Landscape to quickly allow users to close remaining alerts on a form.

IPAD-358.name: The Provider name needs to print out on the forms.

Currently, the Broad forms do not have a field for provider names - just for signature.  The provider name fields would likely need to be added.  On the CRNA/MD fields in PreOp and Anesthesia record the signature needs to be accompanied by a printed version of the provider name.  

After discussion with Craig, the correct way to meet this need will be to add name fields to both forms and populate those name fields with the name of the user who tapped on the signature field. Adding metadata

IPAD-374.name: A user action of View should be logged in the Audit Log when a form is viewed.

This means that even though the user may be switching back and forth between form tabs within the same case, multiple audit log records will be generated.  This is desirable because in the event of an audit the exact path of the user can be determined.

Proposed Solution:  Rather than use valuable space to display the user name all the time, the gear icon in the top right can be used to display the user name.  The user should tap on the gear icon and see the user name displayed above the other options.

IPAD-399.name: The user should not be able to print the form if the vitals have not yet reached the server.
IPAD-399.description:
Business Need: The iPad currently allows the user to print the Anesthesia record even if the vitals have not pushed to the server.  This is an issue because the user will expect this data to print since it is on the iPad.

Currently button checks to see if an internet connection exists.  This enhancement would add validation that the queue for vitals is clear.  In the event that a queue exists, a UI element (spinning wheel) should display to indicate to the user that the iPad is waiting before printing.  The user should be able to cancel if they are not willing to wait for the vitals.

IPAD-400.name: The full list of users should be available on the login page when the user is entering data into the username
IPAD-400.description:
Currently when the login page is visited in Broad production, only certain users are visible (it appears to be just the ones who have logged in?).  It should be all of them.

This was due to the fact that for some reason, the user does not set a hashed password on a newly created user - the hashed password is only set when the user logs in to the web, or when the administrator changes the password manually.

Out of caution, the server did not send these to the iPad - which is good, because the iPad would not have liked it very much.

The fix is to have the server send the users to the iPad anyway (if the iPad is running new enough software - otherwise it will continue not to do so for backwards compatibility). And then on the iPad, if the user has no hashed password/keystore, it will authenticate to the server instead of locally.

----

Testing

You may do all testing with an updated server.

* Create new user with some password. Do not log in to web.
* On old iPad version:
** Refresh user list (hit 'i' button on login screen, then "Return to Login Screen")
** Verify absence of new user.
* On new iPad version:
** Refresh user list
** Verify presence of new user.
** Attempt login to new user.
** Should take slightly longer than normal because it will have to log in via the server, but it should be successful - and then force you to change your password.
** After login, you should be able to see the user on the old version iPad after a user refresh.

Technically you can reproduce this by going into any user in Couch (whose password you know) and deleting their hashed password.

IPAD-452.name: VOID forms data gets thrown away
IPAD-452.description:
If you void or close a form from one iPad/the web while another iPad is editing the form (easiest to play with if the second iPad is in airplane mode), then when you bring the iPad back online, all of the changes made it made to the form while offline be discarded.

This change causes the formerly discarded changes to be preserved, but not incorporated into the form.

----

Normally when the iPad sends changes to the server, two things happen:

* the changes are merged into the corrections object on CouchPageAddress
* the changes send from the iPad in that batch are thrown into a new attachment on the CouchPageAddress called "tabletChanges/a_long_id". Those changes are also given type information ("tabletchanges") in the attachmentAttributes object.

If the form is closed/void, the changes are thrown away.

With this change, if the form is closed/void, the changes are still not merged into the corrections object, but they are thrown into a new attachment as usual. In addition, the type information they are given in attachmentAttributes is "unappliedtabletchanges".

That way if a form is voided/closed in error (as happened at Broad in their first week), the data that did not seem to belong on the form is recoverable.

IPAD-457.name: Elegant and easy to use delegate architecture
IPAD-457.description:
The top of the attached screenshot is a rough sketch of what the keypad will look like standalone.

* Cancel and Done, formerly integrated into the keypad, are moved to the standard popup toolbar we use.
* We now have function keys which will vary by input type. Previously we just had F4, and now F1-F3 have been made available by moving Done and Cancel into the toolbar.
* We should try to turn the delete button (formerly "DEL") into the appropriate icon if we can find one.

The button sketches are proposed layouts for the function keys for issues IPAD-409, IPAD-437, IPAD-436, IPAD-402, and IPAD-444. We outline all of the use cases here so we have a central reference for requirements when defining the architecture.

General functionality:

* Cancel and Done continue to work as they do now.
* Tapping outside of the popup generally means Done. If the keypad is in a state where no data has been entered, it should be taken to mean cancel.
* "Clear Value" is a normal prettified button, the width of (or most of the width of) the popup. Pressing it should terminate the popup, and return the empty string as the final value to the caller.
** Any chance this will be hit accidentally? Does it matter?
* The delete button will generally apply only to values that are entered from the non-function keys of the keypad. For date/time entry, it will only delete time characters. For FiO2 or ETCO2 it will only affect the numeric values, not the + or NC toggles.

Function keys:

* F4 should generally be used for delimiters tied to the numbers being entered ("." for decimals, ":" for times, "/" for dates).
* Outside of that, I think additional functionality should be added top to button - F1, F2, F3.
* I imagine that we won't instantiate unused function keys - no button will be drawn in those cases.

Input types to be supported:

* BP - functions as now
* Integer - functions as now
* Decimal - functions as now
* Time - needs to display during editing as in drawing (Day MM/DD), but store as full ISO timestamp the way we store times on forms in general. F1="D+", F2="D-" to increment and decrement day if needed. F4=":". Delete button only affects time entry, nothing related to date.
* Date - Should display as MM/DD/YYYY, but store as ISO timestamp, local midnight. Might as well have D+/D- buttons here has well - that way we can default to today for some date fields and they can be tweaked without hitting delete back through the year. But we don't want the default for DOB. They should probably be disabled if a full date is not entered, since we wouldn't know what to increment/decrement.
* FiO2 - F1="\+", toggles presence of "\+" in display. Want button to show in highlighted state when enabled. Display as "123", "123+", or "\+". Store as "123|", "123|\+", "|\+". Implications to both printing and rendering.
* ETCO2 - F1="NC"... Generally same as FiO2. Display as "123", "123 NC", or "NC". Store as "123|", "123|NC", "|NC". Implications to both printing and rendering.
* Height - no function keys. Displays as "4ft 7in", stores as "55". First digit entered is always feet. Optional second and third digits are inches. Printing and rendering implications.

Delegate thoughts:

* NumericInputDelegate
** Delegate object holds local state about what the user has entered.
** - (NSString *)displayValue - what the keypad display should show given the delegate's state
** - (NSString *)storeValue - what value should be returned to the caller if the user taps done
** - (NSString *)validationAlert - if the user taps done now, return non-nil if the data is not valid and an alert should be displayed
** - (BOOL)canAcceptValue - whether or not the value can be accepted even though it has a validation alert
** - (NSArray *)functionLabels - F1-F4 maps to 0-3, return array of strings. "" means no button.
** - (void)buttonTapped:(int)buttonIndex (F1-F4 = 10-13; 0-9 = 0-9)

Delegate will need to call keypad to highlight/unhighlight buttons.

IPAD-426.name: Enhance the iPad print capability to make sure that the print server acknowledged the request.
IPAD-426.description:
Previously a print request was just a piece of metadata added to a form, so the print request sort of synced up with the rest of the form data. It was possible to put a print request in when the network was down (before the print dialog noticed)  - possibly leaving the user expecting a printout to come when the request had not yet made it to the server. And then, when the network comes back online, the print request goes through (possibly minutes or hours later).

These were both considered undesirable.

Now when you make a print request, it waits for all of the data (including vitals data) to get to the server. Then it makes a print request directly to the server, and does not claim it's done until the server acknowledges the request.

DAS-283.name: Need to add an additional indicator to denote which individual forms have been printed - bold the form name
DAS-283.description:
Requirement:
Add an additional indicator of which individual forms have been printed.
Continue to highlight the Case row blue and check the checkbox next to individual forms to identify already printed forms; however in addition to this change the font of the individual form names to BOLD to indicate that the form has already been printed for the Case.

History:
In validating DAS-146, a requirements conflict was discovered between the "identify printed forms" feature implemented for DAS-146, and the "auto-check forms by Case Type" feature implemented for DAS-200.
In DAS-200 it was made clear that Sheridan wanted the Case Type selection feature in the Scheduled page to over-write any checkmarks made by the user. Different Case Types have different default forms. Whatever default forms are in the currently selected Case Type will over-ride what ever was checked or unchecked by the user when that Case is selected for printing.
In DAS-146 it was decided that they would indicate which forms had already been printed by using a colored blue highlight over the row to identify which Cases had already had one or more forms printed, with checkmarks identifying which individual forms had been printed. This was implemented for the ticket and PASSED Validation.
However when the user selected the Patient for printing, the auto Case Type feature removed any checkmarks made by the software to denote already printed forms and replaced them with the checkmarks that matched the default for the current Case Type. Thereby losing the indicator of which individual forms had already been printed.
I sent out an email to Michael Plaisance and Marybeth McGrath describing the conflict with a number of possible options. Option three was to:
3) Add a new requirements to DAS-200 (the Case Type feature) to NOT override the checked checkboxes for Patients that have already had one or more forms printed. Then we can again rely on the checkboxes next to the individual forms as an indicator of which forms have, or have not been printed. 
Michael Plaisance wrote back saying "Needs to be option 3, that’s what they want – if the form has been printed, the dashboard always indicates such."
Further emails between Luke Driscoll and Michael Plaisance decided to bold the font name for the individual forms to indicate it had already been printed rather than changing the behavior of the Case Type auto check implemented in DAS-200.
This ticket is to implement that change.

AP-50.name: SSO / Authentication
AP-50.description:
Create a gem that supplies a before_filter that authenticates against the dashboard.

Background: 

The user logs in at https://dashboard.shareableink.net. This is a Java servlet container that will establish the usual JSESSION_ID cookie.

Apollo will be accessed at https://dashboard.shareableink.net/apollo, and hence Rails will also get the JSESSION_ID.

The gem will use the JESSION_ID to make a call back into an API exposed by the dashboard to authenticate the JESSION_ID and return user credentials.

The location of Dashboard API is http://tangx01:8090/api/; this should be parameterized in environment config file

The before_filter should be the default on the application controller.

If the JESSION_ID isn't present on execution of an controller, redirect to the gem's own login page. This will make testing easier as we won't have to go through the main dashboard URL.

The login page gathers login credentials and calls into the Dashboard  API to authenticate. The API will return a JESSION_ID cookie; return this cookie to the browser and the rest of the authentication path for future calls should be like normal.

AP-62.name: Organization A should not see Organization B's data
AP-62.description:
Customer A should not see Customer B's data. This story builds out the access control plumbing.

This the beginnings of a very simple authorization scheme. The authentication API will return user credentials, including the organization  of the user. Each organization will correspond to a mongodb database. A user at organization XYZ must only be able to query mongodb database XYZ.

Every controller will need a before_filter to check for organization authorization. 

User credentials will also contain one or more facility for the user. A user with access to facilitiees A and B must only be able to retrieve data for A and B. The facility code is stored on each case in MongoDB. Every query to mongodb originating from the drag-and-drop UI must filter by the user's facility access.

Note that we eventually want the concept of a super user that can access all organizations and customers.

FFBM-158.name: FORML enhancements - Definition / Requirements
FFBM-158.description:
Identified new requirements for the FORML spec during a conversation with Craig for FFBM-143.  There is some work here to figure out the right way to express in FORML and update the spec etc.

There are some minor enhancements like new Element and Display properties.

Also a category of constructs for 'external references'. These are interdependencies between Form Elements.

external references (UI independent)

- dateField - field to populate with current time when this field is populated (signatures)
- nameField - field to populate with current user when this field is populated (signatures)
- providerTypeField - radio to check with md/crna (signatures)
- minField - field this field must be greater than (times)
- globalField - publish/subscribe field name
- globalFieldLinkAttributes - when to publish/subscribe

IPAD-389.name: Provider population not right when multiple providers have the same last name
IPAD-389.description:
There are now four different provider lexicons hooked up to the broad forms:

* surgeons
* MDs (anesthesiologists)
* CRNAs
* MDs&CRNAs

Some of these are tied to fields that are tied to signatures.

When signing a signature field with an associated field/lexicon, the iPad attempts to match the user's name to an entry in the lexicon. If it finds a match in the lexicon, it fills in the field. If not, it doesn't.

It currently matches by assuming the user's name is in the format "First Last" (this is subject to evolve as needed). Based on this, it generates two strings:

* "Last"
* "Last F" (last name plus first initial)

If it finds a match to one of these in the associated lexicon, it fills in the field.

The lexicon is populated with "Last" in general, but also "Last F" in the case of otherwise duplicated last names.

To test this, you're best off temporarily changing your own user's name to match (or not match) one of those in the lexicon.

IPAD-369.name: iPad has no logic to "give up" posting changes to server that will never be accepted

IPAD-407.name: Using vitals entry popover when clinical type is added or removed results in later crash
IPAD-407.description:
The crash referenced (and circumvented) by IPAD-398 can be reproduced by:

* Bring up the same vitals tab on two iPads.
* Add an EKG value to either iPad.
* Make sure they are syncing (see EKG appear on second iPad).
* On iPad 1, go to setup.
* On iPad 2, tap the EKG value to edit it. Leave the edit / new vital popover choice up.
* On iPad 1, check/uncheck Propofol (mcg/kg/min).
* On iPad 2, wait for Propofol to appear/disappear.
* On iPad 2, tap edit for the EKG value.

iPad 2 should crash.

This happens because the addition/deletion of a new type of vital causes the views to reload - and the view that was the delegate for the popover becomes disowned by the view hierarchy. But when you tap an item on the popover, that view gets a message and attempts to open another popover associated with itself, which is illegal.

There may be a few different bugs/variations associated with this view reload process. IPAD-170 might also be a result of this in some way.

I suspect the short term fix for this is to reassign the responsibilities of the delegate CaptureGridViewController, which is not transient, but is the stable root of these views. The longer term fix is to have the views adapt without fully reloading.

IPAD-250.description:
Currently the iPad doesn't keep track of what a required vs normal alert means. It treats them all as normal alerts.

To get required alerts in, edit AlertsDefault.groovy and change some appropriate alerts to be required. For example, change "alert" in:

    alert "1902", "Patient Safety", "Alarms On",
        addressed("anesEnd.hours"),
        addressed("anesEnd.minutes"),
	not(checked("patientSafety.audibleAlarms.Yes"))

to "requiredAlert":

    requiredAlert "1902", "Patient Safety", "Alarms On",

IPAD-79.name: Update SystemProblem to flag absence of new form metadata
IPAD-79.description:
The SystemProblem class on the iPad recognizes and flags various configuration errors, including on the server, and so makes various setup problems easier to debug.

It needs to be updated to detect the absence of the attachments:

* meta
* tagMap

It already handled the patches attachment.

As a bonus, this fixes the problem where the iPad didn't notice automatically when the attachments were added (within a minute or so).

Testing:

* Pick a victim form.
* Find the form definition for the form in Couch. (Using the TabletFormDefinition byFormName view.)
* Download all three of meta, tagMap, and patches attachments from the form definition.
* Delete those three attachments from the form definition. (I believe (x) each, then save document.)
* Clear data on your friendly neighborhood iPad.
* Log in to the iPad against the relevant customer.
* It should give warnings about all three missing attachments.
* For each missing attachment:
** Re-upload the attachment to the form definition document.
** Wait a minute or so. The warning for that attachment from the iPad should disappear.
* After uploading the final attachment, the iPad should proceed to the encounter list.

Previously the iPad would not warn about missing meta or tagMap attachments, and miscellaneous misbehavior would ensue. For tagMap, for example, time and date fields would not work correctly.

IPAD-157.name: Patient Profile form selections should be reflected in form tabs
IPAD-157.description:
Checkbox behavior when creating a patient manually:

While creating a patient, before you hit "continue", the checkboxes do nothing but note which forms you would like created. No forms are actually created (or voided) until you hit "continue." Once you do so, the forms are created and saved to disk, to eventually reach the server.

Checkbox/form behavior when tapping on a patient from the server that has no case:

A case is created, and a default set of forms are also created and saved to disk, to eventually reach the server. The default forms are those that have "preSelected": true set in their meta information.

Checkbox/form behavior when tapping on a patient from the server that has a case:

Already existing forms are shown in the tabs and checkboxes.

General checkbox behavior for existing encounters:

When you check a new form for an existing encounter, that form is created only in memory. The form will not be saved to disk until you go to the form and actually make a change to it. As a consequence, if you check a form and then leave the patient, and then return, the form will be unchecked, as the in-memory form will have been discarded.

This is to prevent wanton creation and destruction of forms when people check and uncheck the forms on the patient profile screen just for fun.

So if you check a form and then edit it, it will be saved to disk.

Unchecking any form that has been saved to disk will result in voiding the form - deleting it from memory, and telling the server to void it.

At the moment, there is no warning to prevent you from editing a form you have added data to. That is addressed in IPAD-144, not yet implemented.

In addition, while addition and removal of forms will be reflected on other iPads, it will not yet show live (IPAD-245). That is, if you are looking at a patient at the time forms are added or removed, the changes will not show. But if you visit the patient some time (two or three minutes) after the changes are made, you should see them.

IPAD-201.name: Store clinical data definitions in Couch
IPAD-201.description:
Clinical data definitions are currently hard-coded (as a JSON document) on both the iPad and in Ruby code. The definitions need to be moved somewhere more appropriate.

Luke and I decided to put them in a new document type, as JSON (not an attachment), allowing relatively easy editing in Couch itself.

As of this change, there is a new Couch database per client called _customerCode__refdata intended to hold slowly-changing reference data for performance reasons.

Its first resident is the dataDefinitions document type. Specifically the document dataDefinitions_anesRec holds all of the data definitions used for clinical capture on the iPad.

Now, when setting up an iPad fresh (clear data), the iPad will expect to see this document as well, and if it isn't present, it will hang on "Loading forms..." until it is.

The Ruby code accessing this document instead of its hard-coded copy will be handled by IPAD-248.

IPAD-305.name: Case/encounter created on iPad has "Unknown" provider

IPAD-88.name: New vitals input UI
IPAD-88.description:
This story contains a new vitals entry UI which is more consistent with the rest of the clinical data entry interface, and also easier to use.

By tapping on a  time in the vitals graph, a new view comes up allowing direct editing of all vitals types (heart rate, non-invasive blood pressure, O2 saturation, invasive blood pressure, and mean blood pressure).

This UI follows both taps and drags in most cases (generally moving the value nearest your finger).

It does not allow the entry of invalid values unless the validation switch is turned off.

* When dragging, the configured valid range for the vital is highlighted, and you are not allowed to drag the value out of the range.
* If you drag a systolic below a diastolic or vice-versa, the values are swapped so that systolic is always greater.
* If you attempt to complete the vitals (with done, next, or previous) and you have a partially entered blood pressure (sys or dia only) you are given an alert rather than allowed to proceed.

An individual vital may be unset by dragging it to the bottom area.

No changes (either by dragging or the other buttons) are saved until you leave the view with Done, Next Value, or Previous Value. 

There are several buttons:

* "Cancel" ends the view without saving the changes on screen.
* "Done" ends the view, first saving the changes on screen, if any.
* "Clear All" clears all vitals values to zero, but does not save.
* "Undo Changes" reverts the controls to the values as they are currently saved, if any.
* "Copy Previous" copies over the vitals values from the 5-minute-ago interval, but does not save.
* "Previous Time" saves whatever changes have been made to the current time, and then steps back 5 minutes.
* "Next Time" saves whatever changes have been made to the current time, and then steps forward 5 minutes.

IPAD-230.name: Capture times in ISO format
IPAD-230.description:
The iPad needs to capture dates/times in ISO date-time format and not just as hh:mm or mm/yy/dd. This is critical for analytics.

All dates and times on the Broad forms and other future forms are captured in the format yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH:mm:ss.SSS, e.g. 2013-02-13T15:26:27.000, relative to GMT. Current forms used in testing in the HCA system continue to use the old time formats.

* Date-only fields will have time components, but they should be set to represent midnight local time (converted to GMT).
* Time-only fields are really a fiction for the form. They will include full date and time information, so that analytics and other software does not have to do any hocus-pocus to determine the date that the time belongs to.
* To help ensure the validity of these fields, basic minimum constraints are placed on many times. For example:
* Most times on the anesthesia form cannot be filled out until the anesthesia start time has been entered. And then, values before the anesthesia start time are not allowed. In addition, on all time fields, values in the future are not allowed. Currently taps on time fields that require other time fields to be entered first are silently ignored. We need to decide how we want to handle this.
* We expect that we will not support web validation of iPad forms.
* The new date storage can be observed by looking at the corrections field in the CouchPageAddress.

Printing date/time values on these kinds of forms properly won't happen until IPAD-231 is completed.

IPAD-233.name: Redis subscription concurrency problem
IPAD-233.description:
Mojave's underlying Redis support framework (Spring Data with Jedis connector) has a concurrency problem with subscriptions.  Adding new subscriptions for channels after the Redis subscription connection has already been established introduces a race condition on the Jedis Client instance associated with the connection.

Two Threads are writing to and flushing the Jedis Client instance's output buffer.  This can lead to garbage commands sent to Redis and successful subscribe commands for garbage channels.

IPAD-253.name: Store clinical capture templates in Couch
IPAD-253.description:
Clinical capture templates are presently hard-coded in the iPad. We'll need to be able to edit them for the customer without releasing new iPad software.

This change moves the templates into the "captureTemplates" document type in the _customerCode__refdata database. The values listed correspond to the ids in the data definitions.

The ids in the data definitions are generated by concatenating (with a ".") the id/label of each step in the definition hierarchy. If the hierarchy has a label and no id, the label is used for the id.

IPAD-276.name: Incorporate open-source crash dump for ad-hoc builds
IPAD-276.description:
Right now if an ad-hoc build crashes at a customer site, we have no way of getting the crash dump back. Apple only supports delivering us crash dumps though the app store deployment process.

We can incorporate an open source package to capture crash dumps, then deliver them with our existing log file infrastructure.

To test:

* Log into tweb01 (potentially tweb02, but stuff doesn't seem to go there too often) and cd to the logs directory, for example:
** cd /opt/si/dashboard/logs/tablet/brdbrsc33432
* Log in to the iPad app.
* Do something that causes the app to crash.
* ls -lt | head on tweb01 to see what logs are there.
* Start the app. The app should immediately (without logging in, and within a couple of seconds if the network is OK) send a crash dump to the server.
* ls -lt | head
** You should see a file like "iPad.1C-AB-A7-90-F5-D6.20130315T124842.crash" that wasn't there before.
** This is approximately the same format as the crash dumps you're used to getting out of iTunes and sending.

Notes:

If the network is not available, the crash dump just sits in a queue with the other log files that are potentially backed up. You can see this queue in "Debugging Information" under "Archived logs". The crashes and logs are listed in the order in which they will be sent to the server (usually once every 5 minutes until empty). This queue is normally only processed while someone is logged in to the device, but on app startup if there's a new crash available, we will send the oldest crash to the server immediately.

("Debugging Information" is available from the gears menu after you shake the iPad.)

Crashing:

If you can't find a way to crash the app, awesome! But I did add a convenience function to do so. There's a new option on the gears menu, after you shake it, called "Crash Application".

IPAD-306.name: Memory handling tweaks
IPAD-306.description:
It appears that Warren is starting to encounter out of memory conditions on the iPad. Out of memory conditions do not generate crash dumps, so it's hard to be certain. However, I do know of one case that can cause out of memory that I can work around. So for this change:

* Log to the log file when memory becomes low, so we have a better idea when out of memory is occurring.

I don't have a good way to test the logging of the memory warning outside of dev, but I did try it out. It's just a log call.

But you can test the other by using the HCA anesthesia form and setting an anesthesia start date + time to three days ago. The go to the vitals and verify you can only see 18 hours worth of data. (In previous builds, you could keep scrolling and scrolling until the app crashed from running out of memory; you probably would not make it to the present time I think this is one crash Warren may have seen.)

IPAD-177.name: Log files rejected by nginx should be deleted
IPAD-177.description:
nginx rejects HTTP entity bodies larger than about 1M with a 413 error. When submitting log files, this causes the iPad to get hung up attempting to resubmit the same log file repeatedly.

When the iPad gets this HTTP error, it should log the name and file size of the offending log file, and then delete it.

Testing:

To test this, you need to be able to generate a large log file. I've added an option to the debug menu, "Create Large Log" to allow this. This creates a >1M file called "iPad.000000.log".

The iPad checks every 5 minutes to see if there are logs to send. If there are, it sends one. The test large log is named so that the iPad will attempt to send it before any other logs. So within 5 minutes of creating the large log (it really only lets you create one at a time), the iPad should attempt to send it, and you should see in the iPad log:

{code}
2013-03-28 11:27:22.642 23145:c07 5162 W Update:LogUpdate.m Server rejected log file iPad.000000.log (1247090 bytes) with 413 - removing
{code}

You can inspect the list of logs to be sent by choosing "Debugging Information" from the debug menu. You will be able to see the large log in this list after you create it, unless you're unlucky and it has been purged. Then if you wait at most five minutes you should be able to return to this screen and note its absence.

You can look for the quoted log snippet by scrolling through "Logs" from the debug menu.

Alternatively, you can select "Roll Logs" on the iPad, login, wait up to five minutes for the logs you just rolled to be pushed for the server, then search the log file on the server.

IPAD-238.name: The user should not have to complete the Operative Report, Catheter and Operative Report, Block fields that can be completed with pre-fill data

IPAD-370.name: Support vitals screen pulling start/end times from Broad anesthesia form
IPAD-370.description:
In the absence of anesthesia start and end times set on the form, the vitals screen starts from:

* the earliest vital entered, or
* the nearest 15 minute mark before the current time

Similarly, it ends at the current time.

When originally implemented, we only had the HCA anesthesia forms, and I added code so that it would honor those start/end times as much as made sense:

* If there's a start time on the form, and it's not after a vital that has already been entered, start the graph at that time (the nearest 15 minute mark before).
* If there's an end time on the form, do not extend the graph past that end time.

I forget the exact logic, but I think it makes sense for reasonable use cases.

Anyway, I just hooked that existing logic up to the Broad anesthesia form as well. It looks like it may need some work around the end time, some of it related to the issue that Justin already filed about the end time advancing beyond the 16h hard-coded limit.

IPAD-385.name: Auto-zoom forms on iPad
IPAD-385.description:
In order to improve readability of forms on the iPad, we have begun drawing them to an aspect ration more suitable for the iPad (such as 5.5in x 10in). However this is still done in the scope of an 8.5 x 11 page, so we want the iPad to automatically zoom in to fill the screen with the smaller layout.

For now, the iPad will perform this zoom and limit the user to scrolling within the useful part of the page. Until they pinch-zoom. Once they pinch-zoom in or out, they will have full scrolling control, not limited to the useful page, but to the blank borders as well.

This is not ideal, but it seems I am just too tired at this point to figure it out. So this will have to do for now.

IPAD-388.name: Clearing vitals does not stick

If you clear vitals, they disappear from the graph as expected. But then when you leave the patient and return, the vitals come back.

IPAD-439.name: iPad should accept bad UTF8 data
IPAD-439.description:
This issue makes three changes related to UTF8 with the iPad:

* It allows the iPad to muddle through non/bad UTF8 replies from the dashboard.
* It allows the iPad to muddle through non/bad UTF8 replies from Mojave.
* It makes the dashboard send UTF8 data to the iPad.

----

Testing:

Before updating the server or the iPad, entering accented letters into the iPad would result in all form updates from the server failing to get to the iPad. The accented characters would be stored correctly on the server, however.

* After an iPad update, form updates will reach the iPad. However, accented characters will be replaced with a box symbol.
* After a server update, accented characters will make it back from the server to all iPads; form updates will succeed normally.

You can also enter accented characters in clinical notes. The iPad change will accept them back from the server substituting the box symbol. A Mojave fix to allow full UTF8 support is in progress.

IPAD-447.name: Manual encounters can get stuck on iPad
IPAD-447.description:
If there are multiple encounter updates available at the beginning of an encounter submission cycle (once per minute), the first will be sent to the server and subsequent ones will be stuck on the iPad. They will not escape the iPad until the app is restarted (kill app from task bar, restart iPad).

(That is how I remember the failure mode working - create 2, one makes it, things get stuck. But it might have been create 3, one makes it, another makes it to the server but jams in the iPad, and the third never makes it off.)

To reproduce, method 1:

* Make changes to two encounters in rapid succession on iPad A, between encounter update cycles.
** one create + one cancel, or
** two cancels, or
** whatever can be easily observed. Number of encounters changed is what counts, not number of changes to an encounter.
* Observe one change propagate to iPad B within 2 minutes, but not the other.
* Kill & restart the app on iPad A.
* Observe the second change propagate to iPad B within 2 minutes.

To reproduce, method 2:

* Take iPad A into airplane mode.
* Make changes to several encounters.
* Take iPad A out of airplane mode.
* Observe only one change arrive on iPad B.
* Kill & restart the app on iPad A.
* Observe only one more change arrive on iPad B.
* etc.

IPAD-475.name: Form versioning support
IPAD-475.description:
The iPad needs to be able to support multiple versions of the same form template, since it needs to be able to view/edit old forms as well as create new ones.

These changes have both an iPad component and a server component. In the current case, the new forms have features that the old iPad cannot support, so we will be forcing iPad upgrades concurrent with / prior to the form upgrades in the server.

Note that it will be safe to upgrade the server ahead of the iPad if we choose, as long as we don't upgrade the forms until after we upgrade the iPad.

However, the new iPad software must be able to support the old server and forms.

----

Testing

Keep two iPads, one at the OLD version, one at the NEW.

* With NEW iPad, verify no change in behavior against the old server - iPad creates and works with current form versions as before.
* Upgrade server.
* With OLD iPad, verify no change in behavior. Verify can clear data and set up, create, edit forms.
* With NEW iPad, verify no change in behavior. Verify can clear data and set up, create, edit forms.
* Upgrade to new configuration format, to point at new forms.
* Do not attempt to use OLD iPad at this point. We will be forcing the iPads to take upgrades. Perhaps configure QA in this way as well and verify you aren't allowed to run the old software.
* Verify NEW iPad can see and edit old versions of forms. iPad will not be able to create old versions of forms.
* Verify NEW iPad can create, see, edit new versions of forms as well. (After up to an hour after the config changes are made.)
* Verify NEW iPad can clear data and get set up.

----

New configuration for new forms:

Remove old config:

{code}
  tabletForm "BRDBRSC33432AnesRec", null
  tabletForm "BRDBRSC33432PreOpEval", null
  tabletForm "BRDBRSC33432AnesMAC", null
  tabletForm "BRDBRSC33432AnesOpBlock", null
  tabletForm "BRDBRSC33432AnesOpCath", null
{code}

Add new config:

{code}
  deprecatedTabletTemplates = [
    "BRDBRSC33432AnesRec",
    "BRDBRSC33432PreOpEval",
    "BRDBRSC33432AnesMAC",
    "BRDBRSC33432AnesOpBlock",
    "BRDBRSC33432AnesOpCath"
  ]

  currentTabletTemplates = [
    "BRDBRSC33432AnesRecV2",
    "BRDBRSC33432PreOpEvalV2",
    "BRDBRSC33432AnesMACV2",
    "BRDBRSC33432AnesOpBlockV2",
    "BRDBRSC33432AnesOpCathV2"
  ]
{code}

IPAD-491.name: Need to filter forms/clinicaldefs from incompatible iPad versions
IPAD-491.description:
Periodically we will make an incompatible change to form or clinical data definitions. For example we may change the data type of something to a new type that is unknown to older versions of the iPad.

We need to prevent the older software from being able to see it.

The simplest way to do this is:

* Have the iPad send up its version number with each request.
* Tag each Couch form definition and clinical data definition document with a minimum compatible version number.
* When the server sends changes down to the iPad, have it not send changes unless they are compatible.

We could keep multiple document versions on the server, and serve the highest compatible version to the iPad, but I don't see any reason we need anything that complex. In general, the iPads should take new releases immediately, but since we can't guarantee that, it's enough to just make sure they work as well as before - if the user can log in and use it, it must work correctly.

If you attempt to reload an iPad with on old version with fresh data, it will simply not install (it will keep waiting to get forms from the server that will never come). And this is fine - since the user will not be able to use it correctly.

----

Implementation details:

* For ClinicalDataDefinitions, the storage format has changed slightly. Previously the Couch document contained a dataDefinitions element which was a JSON array of clinical data definitions. Now it is an object with two elements: "clinicalVersion", a number representing the clinical data version compatibility number, and "definitions", which contains the JSON array of definitions.
* For FormDefinitions, there is just a "clinicalVersion" number added to the meta attachment JSON.
* For all data calls, the iPad sends up its clinicalVersion.
* If the iPad's clinicalVersion number is greater than or equal to the clinicalVersion number for a given form or set of data definitions (and the data is not already on the iPad), the data is sent down. Otherwise, it is not sent down, and the iPad will keep what it already has.

----

Usage:

* Whenever a non-backwards compatible enhancement is made to a form that requires new iPad support, the clinicalVersion number on the iPad must be bumped, and the affected form's clinicalVersion number must be set to match. Similarly for the clinical data definitions.

----

Testing:

In general, we should be able to upgrade iPads and forms largely independently without breaking old installed iPads. We will consider it acceptable to not allow iPads at old versions to be installed. This issue should specifically allow those kinds of changes.

In addition, we should be always be able to upgrade a server without having to upgrade an iPad (at least immediately - we need to support at least one version back for the iPad), and upgrade an iPad without having to upgrade a server. This applies to all changes made on either side, but is more relevant for certain kinds of server changes, including this one.

To test the cases that will actually apply when upgrading Broad to the next release:

* Prepare two iPads, have one upgraded (153) and one not (147). (147 available as snapshot build on web page, don't have to go through Confluence + iTunes)
* Verify the upgraded iPad works with the old server build. (pre-serenada-master build 337)
* Upgrade the server to serenada-master 337 or later.
* Verify the non-upgraded iPad works with the upgraded server. (IPAD-436, IPAD-437, IPAD-497, IPAD-500 should work the old way)
* Upgrade the PreOp form (ask Craig).
* Verify continued functioning of old iPad with specified fields.
* Verify enhanced functioning of new iPad with specified fields.

IPAD-504.name: Additional demo mode support
IPAD-504.description:
Updating demo meta data (forms, clinical data definitions, etc.) used to depend on updating the database version, which would cause a clear data (which cleared all data on the iPad, not just demo data). Now that we have a live client, we can no longer use that mechanism.

This change adds a demo version number. Updating this number clears all demo data, but leaves other data alone.

----

I believe IPAD-492, IPAD-493 can be reproduced by:

* Install build 147.
* Clear data
* Log in as demo.
* See old forms.
* Upgrade to build 148.
* Log in as demo.
* See extra anesthesia form.
* See incorrect date format.

But if you the upgrade to build 152, or redo the tests going fro 147 to 152, those issues should not occur.

IPAD-531.name: Printing needs to find new ClinicalDataDefinitions
IPAD-531.description:
For ClinicalDataDefinitions, the storage format has changed slightly. Previously the Couch document contained a dataDefinitions element which was a JSON array of clinical data definitions.

Now it contains a "definitions" object with two elements: "clinicalVersion", a number representing the clinical data version compatibility number, and "definitions", which contains the JSON array of definitions.

Printing should now test for the definitions object and use it if it exists. Otherwise it should fall back and use the dataDefinitions array.

IPAD-537.name: Can't cancel feed encounter if it has a middle initial
IPAD-537.description:
We periodically see the error:

* Problem with create encounter: Encounter Exists - Middle Initials don't match

in Broad production. I tracked this down, and it happens only for feed encounters that have middle initials, when the user is attempting to cancel an encounter. The outcome is that the encounter temporarily looks cancelled on the device, but is not actually cancelled on the server.

----

Testing:

None of the feed encounters in test have a middle initial by default.

* In Couch, update a patient from the current day to include a middle initial.
* Wait a minute for the patient's middle initial to show on the iPad.
* Tap on a new encounter, then tap cancel.
* Wait a minute for the cancellation to be sent.
* Notice the error in the iPad logs.
* The encounter in Couch will not get the cancel reason set.

IPAD-569.name: Printing cleanup

IPAD-570.name: Make AirPrint usage configurable from server
IPAD-570.description:
New server configuration options in CustomerOptions.groovy:

* tabletUseAirPrint - true or false: If true, use AirPrint to print to printers available on the LAN. Otherwise, print through dashboard (original, and default, behavior).
* tabletPrintInColor - true or false: If AirPrinting, whether to generate color output to the printer. Default is false (B&W).

IPAD-578.name: Send FormL from form definition to iPad
IPAD-578.description:
For implementation/transition time, implement an iPad FORML mode.

* iPad works normally if FORML mode is off.
* Server always returns FORML information for forms if available.
* iPad will show FORML forms if FORML mode is on and FORML data is available, otherwise fall back to normal forms.

This will allow normal development and testing to coexist with FORML development and testing.

For now PDFs will still come from their normal source; the rest of the system does not know about the potential new PDF source either.
